════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
BEAD 1: polylogue-20d.1 — UDS fast path (the hot-daemon concept)
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
PROBLEM: every `polylogue` invocation pays cold Python imports + SQLite open
(3.6–17s observed). The daemon (`polylogued run`) is already always-on with
warm page cache. Route CLI READS through it; keep writes direct.

DESIGN (from the bead — verified excerpts):
- Precedent to extend: the fast-status path already prefers the daemon —
  commands/status.py ~line 950 and click_app.py ~lines 214-221 (anchors from
  the bead; RE-VERIFY, code has moved). Extend that pattern to the whole read
  surface.
- Transport: AF_UNIX socket at $XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/polylogue/daemon.sock.
  TCP stays for the browser extension — UDS is ADDITIVE. An AF_UNIX
  HTTPServer subclass is ~20 lines. Instant-fail when socket absent.
- Probe protocol: socket exists → connect (microseconds to fail) →
  GET /api/health with a 100ms budget. Health payload must carry
  {archive_root, index_schema_version, daemon_version, commit, started_at}.
- CONFIG-MISMATCH SAFETY — NON-NEGOTIABLE AC: the client compares the health
  payload against its OWN resolved config and silently falls back to
  in-process execution on ANY mismatch (archive_root, schema version, daemon
  version). Live trap this guards: POLYLOGUE_ARCHIVE_ROOT from
  .claude/settings.json pointing at /tmp while the real archive sits
  elsewhere — a regression test must seed exactly that mismatch.
- Thin client: NEW file cli/daemon_client.py over stdlib http.client — no
  httpx, no payload models, NO storage imports (the whole point is skipping
  import cost; a client that imports storage defeats itself — add an
  import-boundary test: subprocess-import cli.daemon_client and assert
  polylogue.storage not in sys.modules).
- Send the RAW query string + flags; the daemon owns compilation. Side
  effect: this delivers the #1860 structured-routing behavior the direct CLI
  path lacks — the fast path fixes that bug for free; mention it in the PR.
- Endpoints: REUSE /api/sessions, /api/query-units, /api/facets,
  /api/sessions/:id/read?view=, :id/messages. Add ONE new POST
  /api/cli/query accepting the root-request param dict (cli/root_request.py
  output) to cover the gaps, so CLI flags never drift from the HTTP surface.
- Output: --format json renders via sys.stdout.write of the daemon payload;
  table/plain modes import only formatting helpers that render from payload
  dicts.
- Writes stay direct (user.db is its own WAL file, no contention). Proxy
  READS only.
- Escape hatches: --no-daemon flag + POLYLOGUE_NO_DAEMON env; --verbose
  prints `served-by: daemon (uds, <N>ms)` or `served-by: direct`.

ACCEPTANCE (from the bead, restated):
- Warm daemon serves find/read/messages/facets at 0.3–0.5s wall (from
  3.6–17s). Verify with timed runs; if `devtools bench slo` exists use it,
  otherwise commit a small timing harness artifact — do NOT implement the
  20d.14 SLO framework (separate bead, not yours).
- Golden parity: --format json byte-identical between direct and
  daemon-proxied execution for every read surface on the demo corpus
  (pytest golden-parity test; `polylogue demo seed` gives you a
  private-data-free corpus).
- Config-mismatch fallback regression (the /tmp trap above).
- Escape hatches work and are covered.

IMPLEMENTATION SEQUENCE for 20d.1:
  a. Daemon side: UDS listener (new polylogue/daemon/uds.py or similar) +
     health payload fields + POST /api/cli/query route. Touch daemon/http.py
     MINIMALLY (route registration + health fields only) — see CONFLICTS.
  b. Client side: cli/daemon_client.py (probe, config compare, request,
     fallback) with the import-boundary test.
  c. Wire into the read verbs behind the probe; --no-daemon/env escape.
  d. Golden-parity + mismatch + timing tests.
  Commit after each of a/b/c/d passes its focused tests.

